The host name the remote computer reports for itself. The current value is ${hostName} 41ad45ae-6a69-422f-963e-9716e8529ff0.861ff225-e6cd-4817-b899-8183f2849960.description=
 Detects the operating system that is running on the specified host.

Inputs\:
    host - The host to connect to.
    username - The username to use when connecting.
    password - The password to use when connecting.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. The name and the version of the operating system.
    osName - The completely returned string of the OS name.
    version - The operating systems version.
    hostName - The host name the remote computer reports for itself.
    enterprise - 'true' if the operating system is an enterprise edition
    server - 'true' if the operating system is a server edition
    professional - 'true' if the operating system is a professional edition.
    standard - 'true' if the operating system is a standard edition.

Responses\:
    windows - Remote host is running a version of windows.
    linux - Remote host is running linux.
    solaris - Remote host is running solaris.
    other unix - Remote host appears to be unix based, but is an unknown variant.
    failure - System could not determine remote hosts operating system.

Notes\:
1. The enterprise, server, professional and standard results give more details about what version of windows is detected and are always set to 'false' if a unix system is being run.
2. The operation returns the output of a uname -a for unix based hosts, and the results of osName and version WMI queries for a windows host.

The current value is ${hostName} 41ad45ae-6a69-422f-963e-9716e8529ff0.a97c3304-f05e-4a41-bb54-5fee4b4610ad.transition.description=Solaris 41ad45ae-6a69-422f-963e-9716e8529ff0.a98b4688-10d2-4465-a45d-9ac3626766da.transition.description=Windows XP 41ad45ae-6a69-422f-963e-9716e8529ff0.description=Demonstrates how to use the OSDetector operation which connects to a specified host, and determines what operating system the host is running. It is important to note that the Windows RAS will try to impersonate the username/password provided rather then login to the remote machine using that username/password. If both the Windows RAS server and the server being rebooted are in the same domain then it will work. If, however, the Windows RAS server and the server to be restarted are in different domains then you must specify a local account/password on the Windows RAS server which matches a local account on the target server. If username/passwords match then Windows uses "shadow" authentication to perform the operation. The other option is to deploy another Windows RAS in the same domain as the target server and use this Windows RAS instead. 
Input Parameters\:
host - hostname to connect to.
username - username to use when connecting.
password - password to use when connecting.

Responses\:
failure - System could not determine remote hosts operating system.
success - The operating system was determined successfully.

Extra Results\:
osName - the completely returned string of the OS name.
version - the operating systems version.
hostName - The host name the remote computer reports for itself.

The following results give more refined results about what version of windows is detected.
If a unix is being run, the following results are always set to 'false'
enterprise - 'true' if the operating system is an enterprise edition
server - 'true' if the operating system is a server edition
professional - 'true' if the operating system is a professional edition.
standard - 'true' if the operating system is a standard edition.

Returns\:  the output of a uname -a for unix based hosts, and the results of osName and version WMI queries for a windows host.
